{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01KBp3ZThnesE6MeSzMNJNgF","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Story 4.1: Dockerfile Rules & Validation\n     2→\n     3→Status: ready-for-dev\n     4→\n     5→<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n     6→\n     7→## Story\n     8→\n     9→As a developer,\n    10→I want formalized rules for verification Dockerfiles validated by audit,\n    11→so that \"container missing binary\" never happens.\n    12→\n    13→## Acceptance Criteria\n    14→\n    15→1. **Given** `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` exists, **When** read, **Then** it lists required elements: pinned FROM, project binary on PATH, verification tools, no source code, non-root user, cache cleanup. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    16→2. **Given** a Dockerfile without the project binary installed, **When** `infra.validateDockerfile()` runs, **Then** it reports a gap: \"project binary not installed.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    17→3. **Given** a Dockerfile with `FROM node:latest`, **When** validated, **Then** it reports: \"unpinned base image -- use specific version.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    18→4. **Given** a Dockerfile that passes all rules, **When** validated, **Then** audit reports infrastructure status: pass. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    19→5. **Given** `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` defines required verification tools (e.g., curl, jq), **When** a Dockerfile is missing one of these tools, **Then** `validateDockerfile()` reports a gap naming the missing tool. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    20→6. **Given** a Dockerfile with `COPY src/ /app/src/`, **When** validated, **Then** it reports: \"source code copied into container -- use build artifact instead.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    21→7. **Given** a Dockerfile with no `USER` instruction (running as root), **When** validated, **Then** it reports: \"no non-root USER instruction found.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    22→8. **Given** a Dockerfile with no cache cleanup (e.g., missing `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*` after apt-get), **When** validated, **Then** it reports: \"no cache cleanup detected.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    23→9. **Given** `checkInfrastructure()` in audit dimensions currently only checks pinned FROM, **When** the new `validateDockerfile()` is integrated, **Then** all 6 rule categories (pinned FROM, binary on PATH, verification tools, no source copy, non-root user, cache cleanup) are checked and gaps are reported through the existing audit coordinator. <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    24→10. **Given** no `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` exists, **When** `validateDockerfile()` runs, **Then** it uses hardcoded defaults and reports a warning: \"dockerfile-rules.md not found -- using defaults.\" <!-- verification: cli-verifiable -->\n    25→\n    26→## Tasks / Subtasks\n    27→\n    28→- [ ] Task 1: Create `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` (AC: #1)\n    29→  - [ ] 1.1: Define 6 required-element categories with human-readable descriptions: pinned FROM, project binary on PATH, verification tools (curl, jq), no source code COPY, non-root USER, cache cleanup\n    30→  - [ ] 1.2: Add project-type-specific sections (Node.js, Python, Plugin) per Architecture Decision 5\n    31→\n    32→- [ ] Task 2: Create `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` (AC: #2, #3, #5, #6, #7, #8, #10)\n    33→  - [ ] 2.1: Define `DockerfileValidationResult` interface: `{ passed: boolean; gaps: DockerfileGap[]; warnings: string[] }` where `DockerfileGap` has `{ rule: string; description: string; suggestedFix: string; line?: number }`\n    34→  - [ ] 2.2: `validateDockerfile(projectDir: string): Result<DockerfileValidationResult>` -- reads Dockerfile, loads rules, checks each rule category\n    35→  - [ ] 2.3: `loadRules(projectDir: string): DockerfileRules` -- reads `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` or falls back to hardcoded defaults with a warning (AC #10)\n    36→  - [ ] 2.4: Rule check: pinned FROM -- reject `:latest` or missing tag/digest (AC #3)\n    37→  - [ ] 2.5: Rule check: project binary on PATH -- look for `npm install -g`, `pip install`, or `COPY --from` patterns that install a binary (AC #2)\n    38→  - [ ] 2.6: Rule check: verification tools -- scan for `apt-get install` / `apk add` containing `curl`, `jq` or equivalent (AC #5)\n    39→  - [ ] 2.7: Rule check: no source code COPY -- flag `COPY src/`, `COPY lib/`, `COPY test/` patterns (AC #6)\n    40→  - [ ] 2.8: Rule check: non-root USER -- require at least one `USER` instruction that is not `root` (AC #7)\n    41→  - [ ] 2.9: Rule check: cache cleanup -- look for `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`, `npm cache clean`, or `pip cache purge` (AC #8)\n    42→\n    43→- [ ] Task 3: Integrate `validateDockerfile()` into audit `checkInfrastructure()` (AC: #4, #9)\n    44→  - [ ] 3.1: Replace the current inline pinned-FROM check in `src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts` `checkInfrastructure()` with a call to `validateDockerfile()` from `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts`\n    45→  - [ ] 3.2: Map `DockerfileGap` results to `AuditGap` format for the infrastructure dimension\n    46→  - [ ] 3.3: Preserve existing behavior: no Dockerfile = fail, unreadable = warn, no FROM = fail\n    47→\n    48→- [ ] Task 4: Export from barrel `src/modules/infra/index.ts` (AC: all)\n    49→  - [ ] 4.1: Export `validateDockerfile` function from barrel\n    50→  - [ ] 4.2: Export `DockerfileValidationResult`, `DockerfileGap` types from barrel\n    51→\n    52→- [ ] Task 5: Write unit tests (AC: all)\n    53→  - [ ] 5.1: Create `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-validator.test.ts`:\n    54→    - Test pinned FROM passes for `node:22-slim`, fails for `node:latest` and `node` (AC #3)\n    55→    - Test project binary detection for npm install -g and pip install patterns (AC #2)\n    56→    - Test verification tools detection for curl and jq (AC #5)\n    57→    - Test source code COPY detection for `COPY src/` and `COPY lib/` (AC #6)\n    58→    - Test non-root USER detection, fail when missing or only `USER root` (AC #7)\n    59→    - Test cache cleanup detection for apt, npm, pip patterns (AC #8)\n    60→    - Test all-passing Dockerfile returns `passed: true` (AC #4)\n    61→    - Test missing rules file uses defaults with warning (AC #10)\n    62→    - Test missing Dockerfile returns fail result\n    63→  - [ ] 5.2: Update `src/modules/audit/__tests__/dimensions.test.ts`:\n    64→    - Test `checkInfrastructure()` now reports all 6 rule categories\n    65→    - Test backward compatibility: no Dockerfile still returns fail\n    66→  - [ ] 5.3: Mock all I/O: filesystem (readFileSync, existsSync)\n    67→  - [ ] 5.4: Target 100% coverage on new files\n    68→\n    69→- [ ] Task 6: Integration verification (AC: all)\n    70→  - [ ] 6.1: `npm run build` -- verify tsup compiles new files\n    71→  - [ ] 6.2: `npm run test:unit` -- all tests pass, no regressions\n    72→  - [ ] 6.3: Verify module boundaries: only barrel `index.ts` exports public API\n    73→  - [ ] 6.4: Verify no file exceeds 300 lines (NFR9)\n    74→  - [ ] 6.5: Verify `codeharness audit` runs end-to-end and infrastructure dimension reports all 6 rule categories\n    75→\n    76→## Dev Notes\n    77→\n    78→### Architecture References\n    79→\n    80→This story implements FR23 (formalized Dockerfile rules) and FR24 (audit validates Dockerfile against rules). It extends the infrastructure dimension from Story 3.1's audit coordinator (Architecture Decision 5: Rules as Markdown). The validator approach is \"parse Dockerfile line by line, check for required patterns, report missing as gaps\" -- simple regex matching, no Docker build required.\n    81→\n    82→### Key Implementation Details\n    83→\n    84→**Rules file format (Decision 5):** `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` is a human-readable markdown document listing required Dockerfile elements. The validator does NOT parse this markdown programmatically -- the rules are hardcoded in the validator, and the markdown serves as documentation and a reference for developers. If the rules file is missing, the validator still works with defaults but emits a warning (AC #10).\n    85→\n    86→**Validator pattern:** `validateDockerfile()` reads the Dockerfile content, splits into lines, and checks each rule category via regex. Returns `Result<DockerfileValidationResult>` following the project's Result<T> pattern. Each gap includes the rule name, description, suggested fix, and optionally the line number where the issue was found.\n    87→\n    88→**Audit integration (AC #9):** The current `checkInfrastructure()` in `src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts` (lines 166-190) already checks for Dockerfile existence and pinned FROM images. This story replaces that inline logic with a call to `validateDockerfile()`, which checks all 6 categories. The audit gap format is preserved -- `validateDockerfile()` results map directly to `AuditGap` via the existing `gap()` helper.\n    89→\n    90→**Rule categories (6 total):**\n    91→1. Pinned FROM -- no `:latest`, no missing tag (already partially implemented in `checkInfrastructure`)\n    92→2. Project binary on PATH -- `npm install -g`, `pip install`, or multi-stage `COPY --from` that installs the binary\n    93→3. Verification tools -- `curl`, `jq` present (installed via apt-get, apk, or already in base image)\n    94→4. No source code COPY -- flag `COPY src/`, `COPY lib/`, `COPY test/` (should use build artifacts)\n    95→5. Non-root USER -- at least one `USER` instruction that isn't `USER root`\n    96→6. Cache cleanup -- `rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*`, `npm cache clean`, `pip cache purge`\n    97→\n    98→**Regex approach, not AST:** We intentionally use simple line-by-line regex matching. This is fast, predictable, and sufficient for the rule categories. False positives are acceptable -- this is an advisory tool, not a security gate.\n    99→\n   100→### Existing Code to Reuse\n   101→\n   102→- `src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts` -- `checkInfrastructure()` has the current inline Dockerfile check (lines 166-190) to be replaced\n   103→- `src/modules/audit/types.ts` -- `AuditGap`, `DimensionResult` types\n   104→- `src/modules/infra/index.ts` -- barrel file to export new `validateDockerfile`\n   105→- `src/types/result.ts` -- `Result<T>`, `ok()`, `fail()` for return types\n   106→- `patches/` directory structure -- already has `observability/` subdirectory with YAML rules as precedent\n   107→\n   108→### What This Story Does NOT Include\n   109→\n   110→- No Dockerfile template generation -- that's Story 4.2\n   111→- No `docker build` execution -- validation is static, regex-based\n   112→- No dev workflow integration for dependency changes -- that's Story 4.2\n   113→- No `codeharness init` template generation -- that's Story 4.2\n   114→- No project-type auto-detection for rules -- all 6 generic rules apply universally; project-type-specific rules are documentation only in the rules markdown\n   115→\n   116→### Dependencies\n   117→\n   118→- **Depends on:** Story 3.1 (audit coordinator, `checkInfrastructure()` dimension) -- DONE\n   119→- **Depended on by:** Story 4.2 (Dockerfile template & dev integration)\n   120→\n   121→### File Size Constraint\n   122→\n   123→Each new file must be under 300 lines per NFR9.\n   124→- `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` -- ~40-60 lines (documentation)\n   125→- `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts` -- ~120-180 lines (validator logic)\n   126→- `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-validator.test.ts` -- ~200-250 lines (tests)\n   127→- `src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts` -- modification only, currently 198 lines\n   128→\n   129→### Previous Story Intelligence (Story 3.1 Audit Coordinator)\n   130→\n   131→- **`checkInfrastructure()` is in `dimensions.ts` lines 166-190.** It checks Dockerfile existence, readability, FROM lines, and pinned tags. This story replaces the FROM/tag checking with the full `validateDockerfile()` call while preserving the existence/readability prechecks.\n   132→- **`AuditGap` has `{ dimension, description, suggestedFix }`.** The new `DockerfileGap` maps 1:1 to this.\n   133→- **Barrel imports only.** Import `validateDockerfile` from `../infra/index.js`, not from `dockerfile-validator.js` directly.\n   134→- **The `gap()` helper in dimensions.ts** constructs `AuditGap` objects. Reuse it for all new gaps.\n   135→- **57+ audit tests exist.** New tests must not regress these.\n   136→- **`patches/` directory has no `infra/` subdirectory yet.** Create `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md` as the first file there.\n   137→\n   138→### Git Intelligence\n   139→\n   140→Recent commits show epics 0-3 completed. The project uses:\n   141→- Commander for CLI commands\n   142→- `Result<T>` discriminated union for error handling\n   143→- tsup for building\n   144→- Vitest for testing (2779+ tests as of story 3.1)\n   145→- Barrel exports (`index.ts`) for module boundaries\n   146→- Regex-based Dockerfile parsing already exists in `checkInfrastructure()`\n   147→\n   148→### References\n   149→\n   150→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-operational-excellence.md#Decision 5] -- Rules as Markdown, validator approach\n   151→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-operational-excellence.md#Story 4.1] -- Acceptance criteria\n   152→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md#FR23] -- Formalized Dockerfile rules\n   153→- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/prd-operational-excellence.md#FR24] -- Audit validates Dockerfile against rules\n   154→- [Source: src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts#checkInfrastructure] -- Existing inline Dockerfile check to replace\n   155→- [Source: src/modules/infra/index.ts] -- Barrel file to export new validator\n   156→\n   157→### Project Structure Notes\n   158→\n   159→- New files: `patches/infra/dockerfile-rules.md`, `src/modules/infra/dockerfile-validator.ts`, `src/modules/infra/__tests__/dockerfile-validator.test.ts`\n   160→- Modified files: `src/modules/audit/dimensions.ts` (replace inline check with validateDockerfile call), `src/modules/infra/index.ts` (add barrel export)\n   161→- Module follows existing conventions: barrel exports, Result<T> returns, <300 line files\n   162→\n   163→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n   164→## Verification Requirements\n   165→\n   166→- [ ] Showboat proof document created (`docs/exec-plans/active/4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation.proof.md`)\n   167→- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence\n   168→- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100% of all new code in src/)\n   169→\n   170→## Documentation Requirements\n   171→\n   172→- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated (src/modules/infra/AGENTS.md)\n   173→- [ ] Exec-plan created in `docs/exec-plans/active/4-1-dockerfile-rules-validation.md`\n   174→\n   175→## Testing Requirements\n   176→\n   177→- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n   178→- [ ] All I/O mocked (filesystem, subprocess, HTTP)\n   179→- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n   180→<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n   181→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_015U2Dv9GBzjkQ93L4EzWA3k","session_id":"ef2f2ce5-c013-4ad4-b6dd-a80c40f8ca85","uuid":"0f9b5e9e-93ce-4148-96ac-b5d852edc800","timestamp":"2026-03-21T05:17:41.129Z"}
